stimulus:
Cognitive Functions and Risk Assessment Task Prototype

Drexel University, Lab for Cogntive Neuroengineering

PI: Dr. John Megdalia

We are interested in how you think about the tradeoffs between risks and benefits when treating cognitive deficits.

We will ask you to consider a few scenarios. You will need to think about whether you would choose to use a technique on a patient or not.

In the real word, different treatments are associated with different chances of risks and benefits.

Your task is to indicate whether or not you would recommend one of the treatments based on the chances that it will improve or harm the stated function all else being equal.

Press any key to continue.

Imagine that you are in the position of a physician deciding whether or not to use an experimental treatment for a Short Term (Working) Memory dysfunction.

You will see several cases like this:

Short Term (Working) Memory

Option 1

No treatment

Option 2

First, you should look at cognitive function shown above the colored rectangle ("Short Term (Working) Memory" in this case), then at the relative amounts of gray, blue, and orange in the trial. The amount of these colors represent the chances that the treatment:

Worsens the deficit.

Has no effect.

Cures the deficit.

You should click the 'z' key to pick Option 1, and the 'm' key to pick Option 2. Sometimes the treatment will be on the left, and sometimes it will be on the right.

In any case, your task is always to choose between the two Options- to give the treatment or not.

Here is the function that you will consider throughout the task. Please read the symptoms of dysfunction so that you understand the kind of problem a person would have.

FunctionSymptoms of Dysfunction
Short Term (Working) MemoryThe person has trouble remembering what they just saw or heard

Remember that the amount of each color represents whether the treatment will worsen the deficit, have no effect, or cure the deficit. In the case of Short Term (Working) Memory please make sure you understand what consequences the treatment will have:

Worsens the deficit. The person becomes unable to what they just heard or saw.

Has no effect. The person still has some trouble remembering what they just heard or saw.

Cures the deficit. The person becomes able to remember what they just heard or saw.

When you begin the task, you will first see a cross on the center of the screen. Next, you will see a reminder of what the colors represent before each trial for a few seconds. Then, you will see the treatment appear on the screen and you should make your choice. You will then proceed through the trials until the task ends.
After this slide, the experimental trials will begin. Please do not close the tab or window until you have finished the task.
